{
  format: 1
  name: liasse-json-swap-with-fixed-checksums-stale-identity-unspecified
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["┬¦D.4", "┬¦D.5", "┬¦19.8"]
  tags: ["integrity", "tampering"]
  note: '''Attack: replace `liasse.json` inside an exported artifact with a DIFFERENT
but still structurally valid definition (loosen a `$check` bound), recompute every
manifest BYTE checksum so the swapped bytes are self-consistent, and leave
`manifest.definition.identity` at its OLD value. Does restore detect that the
recorded canonical definition identity no longer describes the stored `liasse.json`?

Byte integrity now passes: ┬¦19.5 has `entries` cover every required direct archive
entry other than `manifest.json`, and `fix_checksums` recomputed the `liasse.json`
entry checksum to match the swapped bytes, so ┬¦D.5 ("Verification succeeds only when
every referenced entry exists exactly once and every checksum matches") is satisfied.
The ONLY remaining inconsistency is `manifest.definition.identity`: ┬¦D.4 defines it
as "SHA-256 over the canonical bytes of `liasse.json`", so the recorded value is now
stale ŌĆö it hashes the OLD definition, not the stored one.

The spec does not pin whether verification recomputes the ┬¦D.4 canonical identity from
the stored `liasse.json` and rejects the mismatch:
- ┬¦D.5 and the import verification of ┬¦19.8 describe checksum matching and entry
  presence, not recomputation of the canonical definition identity. `definition` is
  the one manifest member carrying `identity` (a semantic hash over canonical bytes)
  rather than a byte `sha256`, and `fix_checksums` deliberately does not touch it.
- If the verifier recomputes ┬¦D.4 and compares, the stale identity mismatches and the
  swap is REJECTED. If it treats `definition.identity` as a claimed lineage label and
  trusts it, the swap is ACCEPTED and the artifact carries a lying identity.
The spec decides neither, so the outcome of restoring this artifact is unspecified.
(A byte edit WITHOUT fixing checksums is a different, decided case: it fails the
`liasse.json` entry checksum ŌĆö see liasse-json-byte-tamper-fails-entry-checksum.)'''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.defswap@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      notes: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        body: { $type: "text", $check: ["size(.) <= 100", "too long"] }
      }
      $mut: {
        put: [
          "n = .notes + { id: @id, body: @body }"
          "return n { id, body }"
        ]
      }
      all: { $view: ".notes { id, body, $sort: [id] }" }
      $public: {
        notes: {
          $view: ".all"
          $mut: { put: ".put" }
        }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { call: "public.notes.put", args: { id: "n1", body: "hi" },
      expect: { outcome: ok, value: { id: "n1", body: "hi" } } }
    { export: { as: "a1" }, expect: { outcome: ok } }
    // swap liasse.json for a different valid definition, then recompute every byte
    // checksum so only manifest.definition.identity is left stale.
    { tamper_artifact: { from: "a1", as: "a1x", ops: [
      { edit_json: { path: "liasse.json",
                     pointer: "/$model/notes/body/$check/0", value: "size(.) <= 100000" } }
      { fix_checksums: true }
    ] } }
    { in_sandbox: "s1", steps: [
      { restore: { from: "a1x" },
        expect: { outcome: unspecified,
                  detail: "byte checksums are consistent; whether verification recomputes the ┬¦D.4 canonical definition identity and rejects the stale manifest identity is not decided by the spec" } }
    ] }
  ]
}
